---
import LessonLayout from '../layouts/LessonLayout.astro';
import CanvasDemo from '../components/CanvasDemo.astro';
---

<LessonLayout
  number={1}
  title="Basics"
  description="What is Canvas, how the coordinate system works, and drawing your first rectangles."
  next={{ href: '/02-paths', title: 'Paths & Shapes' }}
>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 1 — What even IS a pixel?            -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>What Even IS a Pixel?</h2>

<p>Before we draw anything, let's talk about what we're drawing <em>on</em>. Your screen is a giant grid of tiny colored dots called <strong>pixels</strong> (short for "picture elements"). Each pixel can be exactly one color at a time. A 1920x1080 screen has over two million of these dots, packed so tightly they look smooth to your eye.</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Think of it like this:</strong> imagine a huge sheet of graph paper where every tiny square can be colored in. That's your screen. Each square is one pixel. When you "draw" on a computer, you're really just telling the computer which squares to color and what color to make them.</p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    Each square = one pixel
    ┌───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┬───┐
    │   │   │ ■ │ ■ │ ■ │   │   │   │
    ├───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┤
    │   │ ■ │   │   │   │ ■ │   │   │
    ├───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┤
    │   │ ■ │   │   │   │ ■ │   │   │
    ├───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┼───┤
    │   │   │ ■ │ ■ │ ■ │   │   │   │
    └───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┴───┘
    A smiley face, 8 pixels wide!
  </pre>
</div>

<p>Canvas gives you direct control over a rectangle of pixels inside your web page. Unlike most HTML elements (buttons, paragraphs, images), which the browser figures out how to display, Canvas is a <strong>blank slate</strong> — nothing appears until you write code that tells it what to draw, pixel by pixel.</p>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 2 — The canvas HTML element           -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>The &lt;canvas&gt; HTML Element</h2>

<p>In HTML, you create a drawing surface with the <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> tag:</p>

<div class="concept">
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    &lt;canvas id="myCanvas" width="500" height="400"&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;

    ┌──────── id ────────┐
    │  A unique name so   │
    │  JavaScript can     │
    │  find this element  │
    └─────────────────────┘

    ┌─── width & height ──┐
    │  How many pixels     │
    │  wide and tall the   │
    │  drawing surface is  │
    └──────────────────────┘
  </pre>
</div>

<p>A <code>&lt;canvas&gt;</code> element is fundamentally different from other HTML elements:</p>
<ul>
  <li><strong>A &lt;div&gt;</strong> holds other elements and text. The browser lays them out for you.</li>
  <li><strong>An &lt;img&gt;</strong> displays a pre-made image file.</li>
  <li><strong>A &lt;canvas&gt;</strong> is a <em>blank bitmap</em>. You write JavaScript that paints onto it, frame by frame if needed.</li>
</ul>

<p>This is called <strong>immediate mode</strong> rendering. You give drawing commands, pixels appear, and the canvas forgets how they got there. There are no "objects" to click or drag — just colored pixels. (We'll build interactivity ourselves later in lesson 7.)</p>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 3 — Canvas Size vs CSS Size          -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Canvas Size vs CSS Size (A Huge Beginner Pitfall!)</h2>

<p>This trips up almost every beginner, so read carefully. A canvas has <strong>two</strong> independent sizes:</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>The two sizes of a canvas:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    1. DRAWING SURFACE (set via HTML attributes)
       width="500" height="400"
       = 500 x 400 pixels of actual drawing space

    2. DISPLAY SIZE (set via CSS)
       style="width: 250px; height: 200px"
       = how big it appears on the page

    If these don't match, your drawing gets STRETCHED:

    Drawing surface: 500x400     CSS display: 250x200
    ┌─────────────────────┐      ┌──────────┐
    │  ●  (perfect circle)│  --> │  (  oval! │
    │                     │      │     )     │
    │                     │      └──────────┘
    │                     │      Squished to half size!
    └─────────────────────┘

    RULE: Always set size via width/height attributes,
          not CSS, unless you know what you're doing.
  </pre>
</div>

<p>Think of it like a photograph: the <strong>resolution</strong> (how many pixels are in the image) and the <strong>print size</strong> (how big you print it on paper) are two different things. Stretching a 100x100 photo to fill a billboard makes it blurry. Same idea with canvas.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="size-pitfall"
  title="Canvas Size vs CSS Size"
  width={500}
  height={200}
  code={`
// This demo's canvas is 500x200 (the drawing surface).
// The component handles DPI scaling for sharp rendering.

// Draw a perfect circle to prove proportions are correct
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(100, 100, 80, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.strokeStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.stroke();

// Label it
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '14px monospace';
ctx.fillText('This is a circle, not an oval.', 200, 95);
ctx.fillText('If it looks round, the canvas', 200, 115);
ctx.fillText('size is set correctly!', 200, 135);
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 4 — The Rendering Pipeline            -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>The Rendering Pipeline</h2>

<p>Here's how drawing actually works, from start to finish:</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>How pixels get on screen:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    Step 1          Step 2           Step 3          Step 4
    ┌──────┐       ┌──────┐        ┌──────┐       ┌──────┐
    │ HTML │  -->  │canvas│  -->   │ ctx  │  -->  │pixels│
    │ page │       │element│       │ draw │       │on    │
    │      │       │      │        │ calls│       │screen│
    └──────┘       └──────┘        └──────┘       └──────┘

    Browser     JavaScript       You call       Browser
    parses      gets the 2D      fillRect(),    turns your
    your HTML   context from     arc(), etc.    commands
    and creates the canvas       to describe    into actual
    the canvas  element          what to draw   colored dots
  </pre>
</div>

<p>In code, that pipeline looks like this:</p>

<ol>
  <li><code>&lt;canvas id="c" width="500" height="400"&gt;&lt;/canvas&gt;</code> in your HTML</li>
  <li><code>var canvas = document.getElementById('c');</code> to grab it</li>
  <li><code>var ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');</code> to get the drawing context</li>
  <li><code>ctx.fillRect(10, 10, 100, 80);</code> to actually draw something</li>
</ol>

<p>In all the demos on this site, steps 1-3 are done for you. The variables <code>canvas</code> and <code>ctx</code> are ready to use.</p>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 5 — The Coordinate System             -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>The Coordinate System</h2>

<p>Every drawing command needs to know <em>where</em> to draw. Canvas uses a coordinate system where:</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>How Canvas coordinates work:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    (0,0) ──── X increases ────> (500,0)
      │
      │
      Y increases
      │
      │
      v
    (0,400)                      (500,400)

    IMPORTANT: Y goes DOWN, not up!
    This is opposite to math class.

    (0,0) is the TOP-LEFT corner.
    (500,400) is the BOTTOM-RIGHT corner
    (for a 500x400 canvas).
  </pre>
</div>

<p>If you've ever used a spreadsheet, it's the same idea: row 1 is at the top, and higher row numbers go further down. Column A is on the left, and later columns go further right.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="coords"
  title="Coordinate System Visualized"
  width={500}
  height={400}
  code={`
// Draw subtle grid lines
ctx.strokeStyle = '#21262d';
ctx.lineWidth = 0.5;
for (var x = 50; x < 500; x += 50) {
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.moveTo(x, 0);
  ctx.lineTo(x, 400);
  ctx.stroke();
}
for (var y = 50; y < 400; y += 50) {
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.moveTo(0, y);
  ctx.lineTo(500, y);
  ctx.stroke();
}

// Draw the axes with arrows
ctx.strokeStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.lineWidth = 2;

// X axis
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(0, 0);
ctx.lineTo(490, 0);
ctx.stroke();
// X arrow
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(490, 0);
ctx.lineTo(480, -6);
ctx.moveTo(490, 0);
ctx.lineTo(480, 6);
ctx.stroke();

// Y axis
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(0, 0);
ctx.lineTo(0, 390);
ctx.stroke();
// Y arrow
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(0, 390);
ctx.lineTo(-6, 380);
ctx.moveTo(0, 390);
ctx.lineTo(6, 380);
ctx.stroke();

// Label axes
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = 'bold 14px monospace';
ctx.fillText('X', 480, 20);
ctx.fillText('Y', 10, 395);

// Mark specific points with pink dots
var points = [
  [0, 0, '(0,0) origin'],
  [200, 100, '(200,100)'],
  [350, 250, '(350,250)'],
  [100, 300, '(100,300)']
];
points.forEach(function(p) {
  // Draw dot
  ctx.fillStyle = '#f778ba';
  ctx.beginPath();
  ctx.arc(p[0], p[1], 5, 0, Math.PI * 2);
  ctx.fill();
  // Draw label
  ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
  ctx.font = '13px monospace';
  var labelX = p[0] + 10;
  var labelY = p[1] + 5;
  if (p[0] === 0 && p[1] === 0) { labelX = 8; labelY = 20; }
  ctx.fillText(p[2], labelX, labelY);
});
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 6 — Getting the Context               -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Getting the Context</h2>

<p>A canvas element by itself is just an empty rectangle. To draw on it, you need a <strong>rendering context</strong> — an object that has all the drawing methods. For 2D graphics, you get it like this:</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="get-context"
  title="Your First Canvas Code"
  width={500}
  height={200}
  code={`
// In your own HTML page, you would write:
//   var canvas = document.getElementById('myCanvas');
//   var ctx = canvas.getContext('2d');
//
// In these demos, canvas and ctx are already ready!

// Let's prove it works by drawing some text
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.font = 'bold 20px monospace';
ctx.fillText('Hello from Canvas!', 30, 60);

// And a little rectangle
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(30, 90, 200, 50);

// Text on top of the rectangle
ctx.fillStyle = '#ffffff';
ctx.font = '16px monospace';
ctx.fillText('ctx is working!', 45, 122);
  `}
/>

<p>The <code>ctx</code> object (short for "context") is what you'll use for <em>everything</em>: setting colors, drawing shapes, writing text, transforming coordinates. It's the paintbrush, the paint, and the palette all in one.</p>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 7 — fillRect                          -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>fillRect — Drawing Filled Rectangles</h2>

<p>The simplest drawing command is <code>fillRect(x, y, width, height)</code>. It fills a rectangle with the current <code>fillStyle</code> color.</p>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>fillRect parameters:</strong></p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    ctx.fillRect(x, y, width, height)
                 │  │    │       │
                 │  │    │       └── how tall (in pixels)
                 │  │    └────────── how wide (in pixels)
                 │  └─────────────── Y of the top-left corner
                 └────────────────── X of the top-left corner

    Example: ctx.fillRect(50, 30, 200, 100)

    (50,30) ─────────── 200px ───────────┐
       │                                  │
      100px                              │
       │                                  │
       └──────────────────────────────────┘
                                    (250,130)
  </pre>
</div>

<CanvasDemo
  id="fill-rect"
  title="fillRect(x, y, width, height)"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// First, set the fill color
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
// Draw a rectangle at (50,50), 200 wide, 100 tall
ctx.fillRect(50, 50, 200, 100);

// Change color and draw another
ctx.fillStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.fillRect(150, 100, 200, 100);

// Semi-transparent rectangle (the 0.6 means 60% opacity)
ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(63, 185, 80, 0.6)';
ctx.fillRect(250, 50, 200, 150);

// Label the first rectangle
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('fillRect(50, 50, 200, 100)', 55, 95);
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 8 — fillStyle color formats           -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>fillStyle — Color Formats Explained</h2>

<p>Before drawing, you set the color with <code>ctx.fillStyle</code>. Canvas accepts many color formats. Here are the most common ones:</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="color-formats"
  title="Color Formats Visual Reference"
  width={500}
  height={350}
  code={`
var y = 20;
var swatchSize = 40;

// Helper: draw a color swatch with label
function swatch(color, label, description) {
  ctx.fillStyle = color;
  ctx.fillRect(20, y, swatchSize, swatchSize);
  ctx.strokeStyle = '#30363d';
  ctx.lineWidth = 1;
  ctx.strokeRect(20, y, swatchSize, swatchSize);

  ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
  ctx.font = 'bold 13px monospace';
  ctx.fillText(label, 75, y + 18);
  ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
  ctx.font = '12px monospace';
  ctx.fillText(description, 75, y + 35);
  y += 55;
}

// Named colors
swatch('tomato', "'tomato'", 'Named color (140+ built-in names)');

// Hex (6-digit)
swatch('#58a6ff', "'#58a6ff'", 'Hex: #RRGGBB (most common on web)');

// Hex (3-digit shorthand)
swatch('#f0f', "'#f0f'", 'Hex shorthand: #RGB (same as #ff00ff)');

// RGB function
swatch('rgb(210, 153, 34)', "'rgb(210, 153, 34)'", 'RGB: values 0-255 for Red, Green, Blue');

// RGBA (with transparency)
swatch('rgba(88, 166, 255, 0.5)', "'rgba(88,166,255,0.5)'", 'RGBA: like RGB but with alpha (0=invisible, 1=solid)');

// HSL
swatch('hsl(280, 70%, 60%)', "'hsl(280, 70%, 60%)'", 'HSL: Hue (0-360), Saturation %, Lightness %');
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Which format should I use?</strong> For beginners, <strong>named colors</strong> (like <code>'red'</code>, <code>'dodgerblue'</code>) are easiest. For precise control, use <strong>hex codes</strong> (<code>'#58a6ff'</code>). When you need transparency, use <strong>rgba</strong>. The <code>fillStyle</code> stays set until you change it — it's like dipping your brush in paint.</p>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 9 — strokeRect                        -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>strokeRect — Outlined Rectangles</h2>

<p><code>strokeRect(x, y, width, height)</code> draws just the <strong>outline</strong> of a rectangle, without filling the inside. You control the outline color with <code>strokeStyle</code> and thickness with <code>lineWidth</code>.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="stroke-rect"
  title="strokeRect with Different Line Widths"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Thin outline (2px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.lineWidth = 2;
ctx.strokeRect(30, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '11px monospace';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 2', 40, 135);

// Medium outline (5px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.lineWidth = 5;
ctx.strokeRect(180, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 5', 190, 135);

// Thick outline (10px)
ctx.strokeStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.lineWidth = 10;
ctx.strokeRect(330, 30, 120, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('lineWidth = 10', 340, 135);

// Dashed outline
ctx.strokeStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.setLineDash([10, 5]);
ctx.strokeRect(30, 170, 200, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '11px monospace';
ctx.fillText('setLineDash([10, 5])', 40, 275);
ctx.setLineDash([]);

// Dotted outline
ctx.strokeStyle = '#bc8cff';
ctx.lineWidth = 3;
ctx.setLineDash([3, 6]);
ctx.strokeRect(260, 170, 200, 80);
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillText('setLineDash([3, 6])', 270, 275);
ctx.setLineDash([]);
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>How lineWidth works:</strong> The stroke is centered on the edge of the rectangle. A <code>lineWidth</code> of 10 means 5 pixels inside the edge and 5 pixels outside. This is why thick outlines can look like they're "growing" the rectangle.</p>
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    lineWidth = 10

       5px outside
    ──────████████████──────
          █          █
          █  inside  █    5px inside
          █          █
    ──────████████████──────
       5px outside

    The stroke sits ON the boundary line,
    half in, half out.
  </pre>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 10 — clearRect                        -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>clearRect — Erasing Pixels</h2>

<p><code>clearRect(x, y, width, height)</code> makes a rectangular area fully transparent — it erases whatever was drawn there. Think of it as a rectangular eraser.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="clear-rect"
  title="clearRect — Cutting Holes"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Fill the entire canvas with blue
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 500, 300);

// Cut rectangular holes to reveal the background
ctx.clearRect(50, 50, 100, 80);
ctx.clearRect(200, 100, 150, 100);
ctx.clearRect(380, 30, 80, 250);

// You can draw on top of cleared areas
ctx.fillStyle = '#f778ba';
ctx.fillRect(60, 60, 30, 30);

// Label
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('cleared areas become transparent', 50, 290);
  `}
/>

<p>The most common use of <code>clearRect</code> is clearing the <strong>entire</strong> canvas before redrawing (for animation):</p>
<div class="concept">
  <pre style="color: var(--accent); font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.4;">
    // Clear everything:
    ctx.clearRect(0, 0, canvas.width, canvas.height);
  </pre>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 11 — Draw Order / Compositing         -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Draw Order — What Happens When Shapes Overlap</h2>

<p>Canvas works like painting on paper with opaque paint: the last thing you draw covers everything before it. This is called <strong>painter's algorithm</strong> — just like a real painter, the newest layer goes on top.</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="draw-order"
  title="Draw Order Matters!"
  width={500}
  height={300}
  code={`
// Draw three overlapping rectangles
// The ORDER you draw them determines what's on top

// First: red (drawn first = on the bottom)
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(50, 50, 180, 150);

// Second: green (covers part of red)
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(130, 90, 180, 150);

// Third: blue (covers parts of both)
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(210, 40, 180, 150);

// Labels showing draw order
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.font = 'bold 14px monospace';
ctx.fillText('1st', 120, 130);
ctx.fillText('2nd', 200, 175);
ctx.fillText('3rd', 280, 125);

// Explanation on the right
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.font = '12px monospace';
ctx.fillText('Drawn first', 410, 60);
ctx.fillText('= on bottom', 410, 78);
ctx.fillText('Drawn last', 410, 180);
ctx.fillText('= on top', 410, 198);
  `}
/>

<div class="concept">
  <p><strong>Key insight:</strong> Canvas has no "layers" and no "z-index." If you want shape A behind shape B, draw A first. If you want to change the order later, you have to clear the canvas and redraw everything in the new order. This is why animation always follows the pattern: <strong>clear -> draw everything -> repeat</strong>.</p>
</div>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 12 — Practical Example: Robot         -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Practical Example: Drawing a Robot</h2>

<p>Let's use everything we've learned to draw something fun — a robot made entirely from rectangles!</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="robot"
  title="Robot Made of Rectangles"
  width={500}
  height={400}
  code={`
// Background
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.fillRect(0, 0, 500, 400);

// ---- BODY ----
// Main body (torso)
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(190, 140, 120, 140);

// Head
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(200, 50, 100, 80);

// Antenna
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(245, 20, 10, 30);
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(240, 10, 20, 15);

// Eyes
ctx.fillStyle = '#58a6ff';
ctx.fillRect(220, 70, 25, 20);  // left eye
ctx.fillRect(255, 70, 25, 20);  // right eye

// Pupils (small dark squares inside eyes)
ctx.fillStyle = '#0d1117';
ctx.fillRect(230, 75, 10, 10);
ctx.fillRect(262, 75, 10, 10);

// Mouth
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(225, 105, 50, 8);

// Chest panel
ctx.fillStyle = '#21262d';
ctx.fillRect(210, 160, 80, 60);

// Chest lights
ctx.fillStyle = '#f85149';
ctx.fillRect(220, 170, 15, 15);
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(243, 170, 15, 15);
ctx.fillStyle = '#3fb950';
ctx.fillRect(266, 170, 15, 15);

// Arms
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(150, 150, 35, 100);  // left arm
ctx.fillRect(315, 150, 35, 100);  // right arm

// Hands
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(155, 250, 25, 25);   // left hand
ctx.fillRect(320, 250, 25, 25);   // right hand

// Legs
ctx.fillStyle = '#30363d';
ctx.fillRect(205, 285, 35, 80);   // left leg
ctx.fillRect(260, 285, 35, 80);   // right leg

// Feet
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b949e';
ctx.fillRect(195, 365, 55, 20);   // left foot
ctx.fillRect(250, 365, 55, 20);   // right foot

// Ground shadow
ctx.fillStyle = 'rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3)';
ctx.fillRect(170, 385, 160, 10);
  `}
/>

<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->
<!-- SECTION 13 — Practical Example: House          -->
<!-- ───────────────────────────────────────────── -->

<h2>Practical Example: A Simple House</h2>

<p>Another example using only rectangles — notice how <em>draw order</em> matters for the windows and door (they need to be drawn <em>after</em> the wall).</p>

<CanvasDemo
  id="house"
  title="House with Rectangles (and one triangle)"
  width={500}
  height={350}
  code={`
// Sky gradient (we'll fake it with rectangles)
var skyColors = ['#0a1628', '#0d2137', '#103050', '#1a4060', '#2a5a7a'];
for (var i = 0; i < skyColors.length; i++) {
  ctx.fillStyle = skyColors[i];
  ctx.fillRect(0, i * 50, 500, 50);
}

// Ground
ctx.fillStyle = '#1a3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(0, 250, 500, 100);

// Grass detail
ctx.fillStyle = '#2a5a2a';
ctx.fillRect(0, 250, 500, 8);

// House wall
ctx.fillStyle = '#8b6914';
ctx.fillRect(120, 130, 200, 120);

// Roof (we'll use a filled triangle — a path, sneak preview!)
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.moveTo(100, 130);    // left edge
ctx.lineTo(220, 50);     // peak
ctx.lineTo(340, 130);    // right edge
ctx.closePath();
ctx.fillStyle = '#c0392b';
ctx.fill();

// Door
ctx.fillStyle = '#5d3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(195, 180, 40, 70);
// Doorknob
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(225, 218, 6, 6);

// Windows
ctx.fillStyle = '#d29922';
ctx.fillRect(140, 160, 35, 35);  // left window
ctx.fillRect(265, 160, 35, 35);  // right window

// Window cross-bars
ctx.fillStyle = '#5d3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(140, 175, 35, 3);   // left horizontal
ctx.fillRect(155, 160, 3, 35);   // left vertical
ctx.fillRect(265, 175, 35, 3);   // right horizontal
ctx.fillRect(280, 160, 3, 35);   // right vertical

// Chimney
ctx.fillStyle = '#7a3a1a';
ctx.fillRect(280, 60, 30, 70);

// Moon
ctx.beginPath();
ctx.arc(420, 60, 25, 0, Math.PI * 2);
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
ctx.fill();

// Stars
ctx.fillStyle = '#e6edf3';
var stars = [[50,30],[100,70],[350,40],[300,20],[450,90],[80,120],[400,130]];
stars.forEach(function(s) {
  ctx.fillRect(s[0], s[1], 2, 2);
});
  `}
/>

